Both deliverables are in place and `transcript.json` validates against the supplied schema (25 iterations, 61 hypotheses, 61 analyses).

**Headline finding:** The dominant signal in the cohort is a single, very large treatment-by-genotype interaction for venetoclax-azacitidine. In the composite responder subgroup `npm1_mutation=1 AND unfit_for_intensive=1 AND tp53_mutation=0 AND complex_karyotype=0` (n = 4,531), ORR is 78.6% on ven-aza vs 15.8% off (TE ≈ +63 pp, Fisher p ≈ 0). Outside this subgroup (n = 45,469), the average treatment effect of ven-aza is essentially zero (TE = -0.3 pp, p = 0.42). A 4-way interaction logit confirms the structure: `t × NPM1 × unfit` log-OR = +2.42 (p < 1e-100), and `t × NPM1 × unfit × TP53` log-OR = -2.64 (p ≈ 1e-13), showing TP53 cancels the joint NPM1+/unfit+ effect; complex karyotype does the same.

**Other treatments** (midostaurin, gilteritinib, ivosidenib, enasidenib, 7+3) show no marginal, adjusted, biomarker-matched, or systematically-searched subgroup benefit on objective response — including in their canonical biomarker-matched subgroups (FLT3-ITD+ for FLT3 inhibitors, IDH1+/IDH2+ for IDH inhibitors).

**Prognostic features** (independent of treatment): ECOG ↑, complex karyotype, TP53, blast %, weight loss, CRP, WBC are each negatively associated with ORR; NPM1 mutation and albumin are positively associated. Treatment assignment is empirically uncorrelated with biomarkers, so the interactions reflect true effect modification.
